messages.text: Investigation: Day 6
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Ford Freeman, initiated June 25, 8:19 AM.
This is Deputy Ford Freeman with the Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office. I know you been poking your pretty little nose where it don‚Äôt belong, Falco.
Excuse me, Deputy?
You‚Äôve been asking all about Duke Simmons.
You dug up some old uniform ‚Äî like that actually proves something.
What do you think it proves?
It proves nothing, sweetheart. You need to mind your own business‚Äî
We don‚Äôt take kindly to outside agencies inserting themselves into our county business.
With a name like Frankie, we at least thought we‚Äôd be getting a man.
Let me tell you, we were sorely disappointed.
I‚Äôm doing my job, Deputy. My responsibility is to the victim.
Libby Dixon ain‚Äôt no victim‚Äî
She ran off to be with some boyfriend.
I‚Äôm not convinced she did.
Bless your little heart. You can‚Äôt even see all the facts‚Äî
Libby took out $200 to rent a room at some sleazy motel.
She‚Äôs just a slut who ran away from daddy.
Careful, Freeman ‚Äî that‚Äôs a missing child you‚Äôre talking about.
We don‚Äôt know what the hell went on in that motel room.
Yeah, maybe she was doing a drug deal or something‚Äî
Like a crack whore.
You are out of line, Deputy Freeman.
What‚Äôs wrong, detective?
On your period?
Fuck off, Freeman.
I don‚Äôt have time for sexist pigs.
I‚Äôve got a goddamn case to solve.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 25, 9:09 AM.
What‚Äôs your 10-20, Deputy?
I‚Äôm checking out the motels in the area, like you asked.
Has anybody seen Libby?
Not since her disappearance.
But the clerks at Motor Lodge and Star 7 recognized her photo.
Star 7 said she checked in a couple times with a second person.
Description?
Male, early 20s, about 5‚Äô11‚Äù with an athletic build and blond hair.
That has to be Bronco.
I think so, too.
Could she have skipped town with him?
I don‚Äôt know. In her texts to him, she says they could be together if they lived ‚Äútwo hours north.‚Äù
They had to be referring to the Kentucky state line, right?
I don‚Äôt follow, detective ‚Äî why could they be together in Kentucky?
Because she told Bronco she wants to be 18.
That‚Äôs the age of consent in Tennessee‚Ä¶
Ah, I see. It‚Äôs only 16 in Kentucky.
Tennessee law states that statutory rape occurs when a person has consensual sexual intercourse with an individual under 18.
But a ‚Äúclose in age‚Äù exemption allows teens 13 to 18 to consent to partners less than four years older.
Libby‚Äôs 16.
Are you saying that Bronco‚Äôs more than four years older?
So, maybe 21?
I‚Äôm willing to bet he is ‚Äî especially since he talks about purchasing alcohol for her.
So did she run away to Kentucky to be with him?
I don‚Äôt know.
The clerk at Wired said he saw her after she officially disappeared on June 18, remember?
It makes sense that she wouldn‚Äôt want me to look for her‚Ä¶
But if she went to Kentucky, why would she drive all the way back down to Newbury to threaten me from an Internet cafe?
Do you think there‚Äôs anything to her ‚ÄúRomeo and Juliet‚Äù reference?
She did attempt suicide in March.
She has an overprotective father, an abusive ex, and she can‚Äôt be with the man she thinks she loves.
Could be enough to push a teen over the edge.
Or maybe she thinks a suicide pact is romantic or something?
You don‚Äôt think she really loves him, do you?
I think 16‚Äôs pretty young.
She probably feels like she loves him.
That‚Äôs not to say she and Bronco wouldn‚Äôt grow apart when they got older.
You know that feeling of continental drift‚Äî
You start out on the same plot of land, but you open your eyes a few years later and you‚Äôre on opposite sides of the world.
It sounds like you‚Äôre speaking from experience, huh?
Yeah. Daisy and I married too young.
We tied the knot a week after I completed the training academy‚Ä¶
And then she filed for divorce when Cate was three.
She said it was ‚Äúirreconcilable differences,‚Äù or something like that.
I‚Äôm sorry, Tex.
Yeah, me too.
But Cate‚Äôs a blessing from God. She makes it all worthwhile.
That‚Äôs actually pretty sweet.
Do you have any kids, detective?
I apologize if that‚Äôs too personal.
It‚Äôs okay. I don‚Äôt have children‚Äî
I‚Äôm married to the job, so to speak.
On that note, I‚Äôm about to head back to Nashville with Libby‚Äôs laptop.
I want to take it to TARU personally ‚Äî the techs should be able to recover her computer‚Äôs memory.
Nothing‚Äôs ever really deleted on all these devices, is it?
Libby wiped the hard drive, but the files still exist there until they‚Äôre overwritten.
So if she didn‚Äôt use her computer much after the wipe‚Ä¶
Those files are probably still sitting there, ready to be recovered.
Don‚Äôt you think we should close the case as a teen runaway?
There doesn‚Äôt seem to be any evidence of foul play.
Libby withdrew the $200 and acquired a fake ID.
She was seen at Wired after her disappearance.
She had a secret boyfriend.
There‚Äôs a part of me that feels like she‚Äôs wasting our time, don‚Äôt you think?
Even if she DID run off, she could be under the influence of a much older man.
Bronco may be planning to take her across state lines to Kentucky.
Don‚Äôt forget Libby‚Äôs a minor‚Äî
That‚Äôs a federal offense.
Okay, yeah. So why wouldn‚Äôt we hand it off the FBI in that case?
Let‚Äôs dig a little deeper before we jump to any conclusions.
Buck up and press on, okay?
Okay, no problem.
Follow up with the tire expert, Deputy.
I‚Äôd like to know for sure if Libby‚Äôs tire was punctured deliberately or not.
10-4, Falco.
The following is a voicemail from Director Philomena Todd to Agent Falco, left June 25, 3:13 PM.
Frankie, it‚Äôs Philomena Todd. I‚Äôve got some bad news‚Äî
The Cedar Creek Sheriff‚Äôs Office faxed over a written request to take you off the Dixon case for a ‚Äúlack of professionalism.‚Äù
Now, I‚Äôm not actually taking you off the case. I know that this is a ploy to get you out of Cedar Creek‚Äî
But I need you to find out whatever they‚Äôre hiding as quickly as you can.
The boys‚Äô club is closing ranks, and I‚Äôm counting on you to close this, Frankie.
Limit your interactions with the Sheriff‚Äôs Office as much as possible and call me if you need anything.
Okay. Keep in touch, Agent. Thanks for your cooperation. Buh-bye.
The following is an email exchange between Agent Falco and Sidney Pickett.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 26, 9:58 AM.
Decker, we need to talk.
I agree.
I just spoke to the tire expert. Libby‚Äôs tire was knifed‚Äî
Deliberately.
He said it was probably punctured with a pocket knife.
Clean cut, straight into the sidewall, just like we thought.
He‚Äôll have the official report on your desk by tomorrow.
Holy shit.
Are you in Nashville with the computer?
I am.
Did TARU recover any information off the hard drive?
They did ‚Äî and it‚Äôs a bit of a twist.
I‚Äôm coming back to Cedar Creek immediately to speak to the Dixons.
Why?
What are you talking about?
We looked at Libby‚Äôs recent Internet searches.
She spent hours upon hours searching the exact same thing, always in the middle of the night, judging by the time stamps.
Okay, well, what did she search for?
‚ÄúHow to know if you‚Äôre pregnant.‚Äù
